Overview¶

In this report, I will focus on analyzing datasets pertaining to two key metrics observed in the customer analytics domain, namely: Customer Lifetime Value & Dollar Value of Sales Attributed from Marketing Campaign. Before we dive deeper into the report, I would like to highlight what each of the metrics really entail:

Customer Lifetime Value :¶

One of the most vital metrics observed at growing companies, Customer Lifetime Value or CLTV, refers to the total monetary value to be gained from a customer throughout the customer's journey in the company's ecosystem.

The premise behind this metric is to be able to predetermine, using historical data, how much a customer is actually worth to the company, therefore allowing a company to perhaps reallocate their resources to pursue newer customers with similar profiles to existing customers with high CLTV values. The CLTV metric is dynamic which means that the value changes over time. Customer with a longer customer history are bound to have a higher CLTV.

Although many variables in this dataset are self-explanatory, some require more explainations:

  • Customer: The customer ID of an individual customer
  • State, Gender, Income, Education, Employment Status, Location Code, Marital Status: Demographic and meta-data about a customer's background
  • Coverage: The type of insurance coverage this individual has signed up for
  • Effective to Date: Expiry date of the insurance policy
  • Monthly Premium Auto: The amount paid to the insurance company on a regular basis, every month in this case, in exchange for insurance coverage
  • Months Since Last Claim: Number of months since customer filed an insurance claim
  • Months Since Policy Inception - Number of months since customer opened the insurance policy account
  • Number of Open Complaints: Number of complaints filed by the customer
  • Number of Policies: Number of insurance policies held by the customer
  • Policy Type, Policy, Response: Data about the insurance policy
  • Renew Offer Type: Which offer sent to the customer for renewal
  • Sales Channel: What sales channel did this customer come from
  • Total Claim Amount: The total amount of claim
  • Vehicle Class, Vehicle Size: Vehicle information provided where an auto-insurance is present.

Dollar Value of Sales Attributed from Marketing Campaigns :¶

Marketing campaigns promote products or services through different types of media, such as television, print, and online platforms such as social media (Source). Marketing campaigns are repurposed for specific goals. For instance: some marketing campaigns focus on improving brand image while others focus on a more tangible return such as prompting target audience to sign up on a website or purchase a product.

The dataset used in this report focuses on marketing campaign data and its consequential effect on sales of a company. The premise behind analyzing this dataset is to determine which marketing campaigns prove to be most lucrative given certain parameters and also develop a predictive model to hopefully allow us to predict how well a marketing campaign might do prior to its release.

A) Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The first step to any form of analysis, I believe, is exploring the data and examining its structure and its distributions. Here I will explore the data on two fronts:

  • First, I will only look at the categorical data and examine their proportions within the dataset. For your reference, categorical data contains a finite number of distinct groups. Example: type of fruits
  • Second, I will move on to exploring interesting relationships between the continuous and categorical variables.

Exploring Categorical Data¶

The visual analysis below yields the following interesting observations:

  • Figure 1: Majority of the customers in this dataset hail from western United States. Interestingly, this may beg the question whether or not any statistical estimates derived from this dataset can truly be indicative of the overall population in the United States. Most likely not but yet this is the data we have to work with.

  • Figure 2: Most of the customers in the dataset do not pursue education after under-graduation. This observance, however, is not a surprising as it mimics the U.S census data pertaining to education levels wherein a much smaller percentage of individuals enroll in master or doctorate programs.

    On the other hand, because we are not given the age of the customers, we can also assume that most customers in this dataset are perhaps still in high school or pursuing their undergraduate degree.

  • Figure 3: We can, however, be assured that any statistical analysis derived from this dataset is not gender biased as it the proportion of male vs female customers is roughly equal.

  • Figure 4: Here we see that most auto claims yield from customers with a four door car or more commonly Sedans. This observation is an unsurprising one as it mimics the general car ownership trend in the US wherein most people own Sedans.

This argument can stem from perspective that urban cities are much more densely populated in the United States & therefore one could expect the population, especially the highly educated populous, to live in Urban areas.

However, it is important to note that because we do not possess any information about the age of the customers, this argument can only be a presumption here.

This mimics the general lifestyle in the U.S. Interestingly enough, we also see that most single individuals, in the dataset, live in the suburbs. This can perhaps be due to the fact that a lot of the customers that are still in high school and therefore living in the suburbs with their parents (as referenced in Figure 4 in the "Exploring Categorical Data" section above)

C) Feature Selection Using Statistical Techniques¶

In order to find the "combination of variables" that will allow me to predict the Customer Lifetime Value metric, I will need to determine which variables or features will contribute the most to the prediction variable (CLTV). This process of manually or automatically selecting features based on some logic is known as feature selection. It is vital that feature selection is conducted as having irrelevant features in your data can decrease the accuracy of the models and make your model learn based on irrelevant, Source_

In our dataset, we possess a combination of several categorical variables and continuous variables alike. In order to determine the "relevant" features, we can perform a variety of statistical tests that can test the independence of one variable when compared to another. The Statistical test to use depends on the type of data present in each of the two samples ( or variables in our case) to compare.

Some of the statistical tests I will use in this case are as follows:

  • ANOVA Tests: ANOVA or Analysis of Variance refers to the statistical technique most commonly utilized to determine whether the means of two or more groups are significantly different from one another. The comparison of two samples is usually done using One-Way ANOVA wherein we wish to compare the groups to find out if there is any significant difference between them.

    In the context of machine learning, one-way ANOVA tests are used to determine the type of relationship between a categorical variable and a continuous variable. The goal here is two-fold, we would ideally want there to be no significant relationship between a categorical variable and a continuous variable within a feature set. This is because we would then be simply using similar two or more similar variable in our models which reduces the model’s effectiveness as generalizing well. On the other hand, we would want there to be a significant relationship present between a categorical variable and a continuous variable if one of the variables was a dependent variable. Answer Expanded on from my Assignment 3 submission

  • Correlation Coefficient: The most commonly used metric to test the level of independence between two continuous variables is the correlation coefficient or the R^2 metric. Ranging from -1 to +1, two variables are can be positively or negatively correlated at varying levels of strength. In the context of this analysis, we will:
    • Test correlation amongst our feature set or independent variables
    • Test correlation between each independent variable and the dependent variable.

"""
HELPER FUNCTIONS
: Here I will define some helper functions which will allow me to perform statistical tests using minimal code.
"""

def chi_sq_test(row,data, a=0.05):
    """
    Performs Chi-Square test between two categorical variables
    
    Returns
    ---
    : p-value from chi-square test
    """
    # Perform Chi-Square test here
    stat, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(pd.crosstab(data[row['column_1']], data[row['column_2']] ))
    
    # Compares P value to alpha. 
    return p


def one_way_ANOVA(row):
    """
    Perform one way ANOVA test between continous and categorical variable to determine association
    """
    mod = ols('{} ~ {}'.format(row['column_1'], row['column_2']),data=a).fit()            
    aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(mod, typ=2)
    
    # P-value
    return aov_table['PR(>F)'].loc['{}'.format(row['column_2'])]

ANOVA Tests__: Independence between Categorical Independent Variables and the Continuous Dependent Variable¶

As mentioned above, we would want there to be a significant relationship present between a categorical variable and a continuous variable if one of the variables was a dependent variable(what we are trying to predict) and the other an independent variable (what we are using to predict). In this case we check whether there exists equal variance between the categorical and the continuous variable, if there exists no significant difference then one cannot be used to predict the other.

Model Interpretation¶

The output of the model yields the following results:

  • coef: The coefficients for each input variable can be interpreted as follows:

    • Direction: Coefficients convey the direction of the relationship between each independent variable and the dependent variable or what we’re trying to predict. A positive coefficient implies that if the independent variable value increases by one unit, the average of the dependent variable will also increase by the value of the coefficient. Vice versa with a negative coefficient where an increase in the independent variable by one unit will cause the average mean predictor variable to decrease by the value of the coefficient.

      • Example_1: Variables such as Income have a negative coefficient which implies that a decrease in Income levels will result in an average decrease in the CLTV by around $9 (in the thousands depending on the scale of the y-variable). One could make the argument that intuitively, the lesser income customers have, the lesser the overall purchases and therefore lesser CLTV & vice versa.
      • Example_2: Similarly, Number_of_Open_Complaints has a negative coefficient. Here as number of complaints increase, the average CLTV value decreases. Intuitively, this makes sense as the customers with more complaints indicates more dissatisfaction with the business and therefore less likelihood of purchasing anything, consequentially leading to lower CLTV values

  • P>|t|: The importance of P-values is in determining whether there indeed lies a relationship between an independent variable and the dependent/predictor variable. In other words, does it even make sense to use a particular X to predict Y? The P-value NULL hypothesis here is that there is no correlation between what we are using to predict (an independent variable) and what we are trying to predict. Therefore, when the P-value is less than the alpha (usually 0.05), we can safely assert that there lies enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis that there indeed lies a relationship between the independent and dependent variable. Basically, smaller the p-value, the better the likelihood that there exists meaningful relationship between the variables.

    • In our case: The model output here shows that Monthly_Premium_Auto, Number_of_Open_Complaints, Renew_Offer_Type_Offer2 and Renew_Offer_Type_Offer4 have very small p-values, indicating that these variables form the most meaningful relationships with the CLTV variable.
      • Monthly_Premium_Auto is significant and positively correlated with CLTV. Since insurance companies tend to charge higher prices customers who have a higher probability of filing claims, it is a given that they contribute more to the CLTV value.
      • Number_of_Open_Complaints: As mentioned above, the number of complaints is negatively correlated with CLTV. As the number of complaints increase, the average CLTV value decreases. Customers with more complaints indicates more dissatisfaction with the business and therefore less likelihood of purchasing anything, consequentially leading to lower CLTV values.
      • Renew_Offer_Type_Offer2 & Renew_Offer_Type_Offer4: Renew offers 2 and 4 have a signficant p-value along with negative correlation. Given that these are categorical variables, it suggests that customers who renewed their policy through offers 2 & 4 are less likely to have a higher CLTV for the company.

B) Forming a Hypothesis¶

As I have alluded to earlier, marketing campaigns aim to serve a variety of purposes. The dataset here comprises sales data, therefore I will assume that the marketing campaign data in the dataset pertains to activity directly related with sales. For instance, urging a potential customer to make a purchase by leveraging the campaign promotion offer. It could be a discount, free shipping or any other form of marketing asset.

I would like to continue my analysis by exploring the following hypothesis: A combination of related independent variables will assist in developing predictive models to predict the Sales Revenue from a marketing campaign.

Note: However, I will convert this problem into a classification problem. The idea here is to bucket the numerical dependent variable SalesInThousands into different groups. Following which I will look to fitting a predictive model that will try and accurately predict if a certain marketing campaign will yield revenue that will fall in one of custom made categories. The following illustration will clarify this concept:

  • Given that the SalesInThousands data ranges from $\$$17.3 to $\$$99.6 thousand, I will divide the data as follows:

    • Sales between $\$$0 and $\$$40 thousand falls in category 1
    • Sales between $\$$40 and $\$$45 thousand falls in category 2

    • Sales between $\$$45 and $\$$50 thousand falls in category 3
      ... and so on

      Note here that each category is not equally spaced. This is because there would be a class imbalance in our dataset. For your reference: a class imbalance is when the number of a class of certain category is far less than the total number of another class of category or categories. Therefore I have categorized the SalesInThousands such that no particular category is disproportionately represented.

C) Feature Selection Using Statistical Techniques¶

In order to find the "combination of variables" that will allow me to predict the categorized SalesInThousands, I will need to determine which variables or features will contribute the most to the prediction variable. Unlike case 1, however, I will employ the use of a different statistical test:

  • Chi - Square Tests: The chi-square test tests the independence of two variables. Similar to how a correlation coefficient tests independence between two numerical variables, Chi-Square tests perform similar tests of independence but only between categorical or nominal variables. The Null hypothesis in Chi-Square tests is that the variables in comparison are independent and therefore have no association. The alternate hypothesis is that they are not independent and therefore have some association between them. Depending on the use case, we can decide when it is good when variables are independent vs when they are not.

    The hypothesis are as follows:

    • The Null hypothesis is that there is NO association between both variables. This would imply that it would be effective to then use the variable to predict the categorized SalesInThousands. We can observe this if the p-value of the chi-square test is less than the alpha (which is usually 0.05)
    • The Alternate hypothesis indicates that there is evidence to suggest there is an association between the two variables. This would imply that it would be ineffective to then use the variable to predict the categorized SalesInThousands. We can observe this if the p-value of the chi-square test is greater than the alpha (which is usually 0.05)

a): Chi-Square Tests to determine independence between categorical features and categorical target variable¶

E) Training and Testing a Predictive Model¶

Given that the task at hand here is a classification task, I will employ them use of a multinomial logistic regression model. Although more advanced ML techniques such as Neural Networks may be applied, the small size of the dataset may respond better to simpler techniques.

My approach here will be as follows:

  • First, I will perform some hyper-parameter tuning to determine which combination of the percentage of test data size and cross validation yields the best outcome
  • Second, I will retrain the model on the "optimal" model parameters and then gauge its effectiveness to predict categorized Sales Revenue

def logistic_model(row):
    """
    Performs Logistic Regression Using a combination of hyperparameters
    """
    # Splitting up data into training and testing
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_dummies, y.astype(str), test_size=row['column_2'], random_state=21)
    
    # Training Model
    clf = LogisticRegressionCV(cv= int(row['column_1']) ).fit(X_train, y_train )
    
    print('Fitting Logistic Regression Model Using Crossvalidation: {}, Test size: {}'.format( row['column_1'],row['column_2']))
    # Testing Model
    return clf.score(X_test,y_test)

Refitting the Model¶

Through the hyper-parameter tuning process conducted above, we observe that a cross-validation value of 5 along with a 7% test size leads to the highest accuracy rate.

In [59]:
# Splitting up data into training and testing
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_dummies, y.astype(str), test_size=0.07, random_state=21)

# Training Model
clf_final = LogisticRegressionCV(cv= 5).fit(X_train, y_train )
# Accuracy Score
print ('Accuracy score for the classification model is ',round(clf_final.score(X_test,y_test) * 100,2),'%')

Accuracy score for the classification model is  53.85 %

F) Interpreting Results¶

A multinomial logistic regression model yields an accuracy score of 54%, which is not suitable for production level work. Furthermore, using a confusion matrix, we can observe how our model performs reasonably well when it comes to predicting whether marketing campaigns will yield sales revenue between $\$$0 to $\$$40,000 , and between $\$$80 to $\$$100,000. However, all other categories are poorly predicted.
